segments.text: 1983 for the history of College Station Project at Colonel Anderson's house.
It was Texas' first effort to assist in the educational process.
This is the oldest state school and the only state school at its inception.
Nothing which is on the campus now was here, of course, at that time.
It was just simply open ranch or farm land.
The school, of course, had
had a very limited group of buildings to house a student body and a meager core of teachers to instruct them.
have no idea how primitive it was in those days.
College Station was nothing.
It was simply the beginnings of A&M College.
All of the people who were here at the beginning served the college in some capacity.
They either were teachers or administrators.
And there weren't many teachers or administrators or students as far as that's concerned.
But they were off to a good start, and that is the beginning of the city of College Station.
There was no Highway 6 at that time.
There was no southern limit to the campus, which was then a barbed wire fence, which is now Jersey Street.
The college grew and a few people, mostly a colored group, constructed a few houses which is on Fireview Street.
They served the college in servant capacity, as all of the professors lived on the campus, in campus-owned houses.
We had two railroads and one road which went north and south and none that went east and west.
This continued as the city grew and the park
which is now south of the campus, began to attract people who were hangers-on or who were professors in the increasingly
in increasing need for such people.
They started, when the space on the campus for campus teachers played out, people began to build homes down in the place called College Park.
until this took place, the whole, that was excellent quail hunting area.
And the road to our east, to this lane that went to the sulfur spines,
That area was used by the early farming sections of the college as experiment stations later on.
I can recall some excellent dove shooting there.
I could go out and get my limit of doves before 8 o'clock in the morning.
This is where City Hall is now?
This is between here and the east.
City Hall?
Where City Hall is?
City Hall?
The City Hall?
Where it is presently?
The City Hall...
The first City Hall was...
at the present north, near the present north gate, in a home over Joe Soslick's studio.
We had one room, one girl, one policeman, and
And no bonded indebtedness.
That's wonderful.
In regard to the no bonded indebtedness, when we needed something, we just asked the people to pay their part.
Now, for instance, we had no water.
We had no sewer system.
Everybody had these underground septic tanks.
We had no metered water distribution system.
Everybody paid the same price.
Later on, when we decided that we should have meters, we didn't think of borrowing money and buying them and putting them in.
We just asked the people to pay for them.
So everybody paid for their own meter, and that's the way we operated in those days.
We didn't have any bondage indebtedness.
As the city grew,
which it did south and then to the east.
It was because of developers doing the building and installing the utilities.
The city bought these installations and paid for them in the fees which they collected by their use.
Let's go back a little bit to the beginnings again.
We had very few students, very few of anything.
The facilities were few and limited.
But we did have installations like the horse barn, and that is where the system building is at the head of Walton Street.
We had Hog Barn, which is where the golf shop is.
And the people that ran the
around the hog barn were bothered about their hogs having cholera, and so they encouraged old Oxbreg and me to come over there with our shotguns and shoot the pigeons.
And so that added, that was quite a
quite an attraction for we two old hunter type people.
Now you might bring that about where we shot the doves when the seeds fell out of the
No, I didn't want to duplicate stuff.
Oh, no, that's quite all right.
So, the flesh, how much of it is there?
That's the firstborn and the hog.
Yes, both of them.
We had a football team and
And we had, I suppose, maybe one or two other types of activities.
But we didn't have much stadium.
They started off, of course, standing up on the sidelines like they did everywhere else.
And then we built a stadium.
and we picked that stadium up at the end of the football season and we carted it over to just east of the Fred's swimming pool where home base was for the baseball team.
And around the baseball field was
place where we had a straightaway on that track was between home base and third base.
And then it went on in that direction, which paralleled the 220 yard section of the track, went on parallel to the Joe Routt Bush, the red start.
And that gives you an idea of how primitive things were around here in the United States.
Now, after a good many years, then the one street, which was Fairview Street,
All these roads, there was very little need for east-west intersections, for east-west roads.
People had, after we got years and years after the beginnings around here, we had some schools over to our east.
Everybody had to come up to New Jersey
to go east or west.
And there were a few roads, but none of them went east or west of more than one or two blocks, and then they'd stop.
There wasn't a single one that the kids could go to school at Old Consolidated without coming up to Jersey and going there to get to Consolidated.
He gave us a street from all the way from the Weldon Road to the school system.
He had to go across one barbed wire fence between Timber and Lee Street.
There's a barbed wire fence that went
in those days, he gave those lots to the city.
And that was one of the finest and the biggest gifts that anybody ever gave the city of College Station.
For a street?
For a street.
He gave us, at one time, he gave us enough
vacant lots from the Weldon Road clear through to Timber Street.
Do you know what street?
So we, Timber.
It is post, it is, uh, oh, I already, I'm slow on my mind.
It is, uh,
It has a little park down here.
Parkway.
Parkway?
Parkway.
Okay.
He gave us a parkway so that the people would go east.
That was good.
I want to recommend to the present city council that they name our street for a personal purchase.
I'll have to tell them that, but that's a good idea.
You get that in there.
That's a good idea.
find some street somewhere and call it Burgess, the Burgess Street.
That's in my book.
Now, and by the way, Herschel Burgess owned that one room where the city council was meeting.
We rented that one room from .
I wanted to ask some information about your background.
Where were you born?
I trimmed the top of that tree out there.
I had a brush file out there.
I can't show you here.
But I cut a whole bunch of poison ivy out of my son's pile.
Oh, I shouldn't be talking.
He lives in Brown, and we live in College Station.
between the two places.
And did you do this recently?
Did you cut the trees recently?
Huh?
Did you do this recently?
Oh, I did.
Some of it yesterday.
Oh, my heavens.
My running gear has been in there for a while.
I don't know about my motor, and I don't know about some of the other functions, but as far as my muscle and bone, they're all right.
Oh, that's great.
Were your parents from Tennessee also?
Who?
Your parents?
I was born in Sparta, Tennessee.
And were your parents from Tennessee?
Well, my parents came over here in 1780.
I go back with five different families to the Revolution.
That's wonderful.
They all came to Tennessee as they migrated.
From?

From the east, the Alliganders crossed over into west Tennessee, east Tennessee, and then they came all across the Cumberlands to the middle Tennessee and started from just this, just barely in the middle Tennessee.
Prettiest country in the world.
Oh, waterfalls there, oh, they'd be so, so, so nice.
Maybe just such a fine place to live.
It freezes every night and thaws every morning.
That's not nice.
But the people there, they figured that if they lived through March, they got it made.
What did your parents do?
Oh, my grandfather was a miller, and my great-grandfather was a miller and a lawyer.
They, of course, Sparta had one raid by the northern cavalry, but they didn't do any damage to the place.
They burned a lot of stuff north of the town there.
But they didn't bother to run down his mill, but they didn't go out and go to the west of it.
My grandparents didn't like the Yankees.
They didn't like the Yankees.
He had slaves.
My son over here has a fireplace.
A lot of the bricks in the face of that fireplace were molded by those slaves of William Anderson.
Oh, I've got plenty.
I can't talk too much about me, because this is about sitting on the station.
So what other things would you like?
Well, I'll tell you one reason.
I told them, I don't like politicians.
I just simply don't like politicians, because they're not good citizens, mostly.
Because they spend your and my money in order to get re-elected.
They waste our money to get re-elected.
All of this stuff going on in Washington is this interest and that interest and that interest has its lobbyists to go in there and buy these people off.
They'll say, you'll never be re-elected unless you support me.
And we got Graham, who's a grand, grand boy.
And he's
He's whipping some of these people a little bit.
But I just don't like, I don't like a democracy.
But it's, I wouldn't give it up.
It's the best we have.
It gives us liberty.
But it also gives us liberty to almost shoot somebody.
We can do nearly anything.
It gives us the liberty to starve or steal.
And we can't keep the people from starving.
Now, way back in the early Greeks, there was a very fine old philosopher who said, our democracy is a wasteful, inefficient type of government.
You can't get anything done if the politicians mess it up.
Now, that happened a long time ago.
Now, they're still doing the same thing, but we can't give it up because we can do... Over in Russia, they say, here, you used to be a serf.
They won't tell it in this.
And you used to feel like you had it in for these people up here, all these rich folks.
All right, you rebelled.
And they shot the rich folks that you were working for
But they put a hole in your hand, and you said, boy, you're going to hole.
And they go over here to this factory, and they give you a card and say, you're working in this factory, and that's where you're going to work, bud, and you're not going to strike either.
Now, history repeats itself.
We're headed for the same thing.
If we don't get strong, Russia will take us over.
And then there'll be more poor folks than there are rich folks, and they'll get rid of the rich folks.
And the poor folks will wake up as slaves of the army and of the people that are running things in Russia.
They're coming right on after us.
They've come already in Cuba, and they're coming out of South America.
And they're spending $3 or $4 to one for us.
They get ready to dictate a peace to us.
They say, will you surrender or shall we pauperize?
You were in World War I, is that right?
You were in World War I?
And II.
I was in both of them.
Okay.
I left the mayor's job to go into the Army, but I wasn't going to run again.
Oh, really?
I was not going to run again because I promised them I would serve one term.
And then I would not retreat myself because they won't like me because I will not buy their water meter.
And I will expect them to do their part.
And people don't like that.
They like to do it for them.
They'd rather you borrow the money.
And I'm just that type.
And I knew, oh, I might have been re-elected.
I don't know.
Because after all, there are more people who believe like me than believe otherwise, I think.
But I don't know about that now.
Well, at least I told them I'll serve one term, just like you're supposed to serve on the jury once at least.
And then, by golly, you don't have to anymore.
If you're a good citizen, you'll do what you're asking for your part.
But people might not want me, because they may not want to buy that water meter.
Now I'm just using that as a ..
But when I was mayor, I shot skunks.
I shot mad dogs.
I did everything that a police department and everything else had to do.
And I enjoyed it.
I was a coach, you see, which I didn't have anything else pressing on me.
If I'd have been the athletic director or the head football coach, it may have been different.
But I was a freshman coach, and I
until I retired and I was here from 1920 through 57 and never was fired and never did quit.
And they named the truck for me.
Is that right?
It's Frank Anderson's truck?
That's wonderful.
Let me show you something here.
It might be well for me to
talk when I shouldn't be listening, but I rather enjoy the fact that I did something at A&M College to help it grow.
I'd been here for about 20 years when Dr. Walton, the college president, asked me to take the commandant's job.
Well, he probably regretted that because I pitched a hot potato in his lap.
I was a tough commandant.
This place needed somebody to start the ball rolling in another new direction.
It needed to grow.
When I came out here, they had 1,700 students, a freshman
found himself in a company of 35 people.
At the end of that year, some of those companies didn't have half of them.
They just ran the freshmen off by tough hazing.
And as a track coach, I had a pretty hard time
keep getting a good track man to come here.
If I got one to come here, they wouldn't respect him.
They'd respect a freshman football man, but they wouldn't respect a freshman track man.
And these boys, maybe the one of them are at home, well, they thought they were pretty good stuff.
And they come here, and some good-for-nothing sophomore will beat his rear and have him to serve them, make their bed up, seniors and juniors and whatnot.
And that was keeping this school from growing.
But I was tough.
I was pretty tough.
And I did a lot of things, among which was start a new tradition.
I can claim one tradition, a legal bonfire.
The student body
used everything that was loose and some of the things that weren't, like the faculty's wood pile or their garden gate.
And all of the outside houses and the other people's backyard, they delighted on bringing those off as a unit.
All right, now my first, after the bonfire in 1935, I'm now the brand new young little commandant.
And a very irate farmer came into my office and said those damn SOBs ran off of my barn last night, log barn, and put it on the bonfire.
And so I just get the captains in and I say, well, all right.
That's the last bonfire you're gonna build.
I'm gonna build the next bonfire.
Now, I took, they had a bull ring.
Everything that they wanted to ram a freshman for, give him demerits, they'd give him demerits.
They didn't care about college regulations, it was their regulations.
So...
So...
So we went from there.
I took the bullring, and I'll explain to you what the bullring was.
These freshmen that were rammed for not doing something.
I got some saws and axes and transportation from the building and grounds department, and I took the bullring on Saturday afternoon and Sunday afternoon, and we went out
between here and the drill field and the airport out there and found plenty of dead or semi-dead stuff.
We brought in, we built a modern log bonfire.
And it just took one year to start a new tradition here.
They're building the same type of
of Bonfire ever since.
What brought you to College Station?
Why did you come here?
As a high school player, I was fast and quick.
And that helped me make four touchdowns against the team that thought they were the state champions until they made a mistake and played our high school team.
That was Fitzgerald Clark at Tullahoma Private School.
There weren't many high schools in Tennessee when I was a youngster.
They were prep schools, privately owned prep schools.
Well, I didn't have anything.
Now, I graduated from that school.
I didn't have any money.
I was offered $40 a month to be freight clerk there at the end of the railroad.
I would have taken it, but a boy from Brandon Training School down at Shelbyville, Tennessee,
sent his son up there, the headmaster, to recruit me and see if I wouldn't come down there and play, have another year in high school.
I was already, I had plenty of credits when I graduated from that high school.
But I didn't have anything else to do, so I decided, well, heck yeah, that'll be fun.
And I went down there and I took French and German and a little more history.
The ex Bible was my Latin teacher.
I took another year of Latin down there.
We used to take Latin in those days, four years of Latin before I got through.
Now, the ex Bible was one of the,
I would say the top six coaches that the United States has ever had anywhere.
We were very successful at this Brandon Training School.
I made a lot of touchdowns for him.
And he was a good Christian man, and he taught a Sunday school class in Mississippi College, the Baylor of Mississippi, which is at Clinton.
Yes, nine miles this side of Jackson.
I don't want to repeat.
He taught a Sunday school class.
And he was very successful as a coach in Middle Tennessee among those high schools.
And there was a preacher at this church where he taught the class, was a graduate of Mississippi College.
And they were looking for a coach.
And he wrote down there and said, boy, we've got the fella you want.
He is a dandy.
And they asked him to come down there.
He made a favorable impression and they hired him.
He came back up and said, boy you're going to college with me.
I went to college with him and I graduated with distinction.
I made six touchdowns against the University of Mississippi in one football game.
We beat Tulane, we beat Mississippi State.
Alabama never beat us more.
Well, we led them at a half one time.
I happened to get loose for 80 yards.
And we led them at the half, but they just beat us down.
But we never played anybody at home because we didn't even have a stadium.
Oh, no.
But oldie X...
got the job at Texas A&M College.
We both went to the war, First World War.
And he says, I've got to be the freshman coach out there for one year because they got a man who's got one year on his contract.
But we want you.
And so he said, boy, you go come out there with me.
You take the job there for a year, and in that year, this man will...
be out of the way and I'll be athletic director and I won't hire you."
And so I've been with that man ever since 1912.
He's been dead for two years.
He stayed with us for twelve years and then he pulled off going to Nebraska and then he came to Texas and then that's it.
That's my story.
And then I've been track coach here for all those years.
What were the years that you were track coach?
The spring of 22.
Since the spring of 22.
Except this time I was out in the Army and was out as commandant.
Now, the board of directors came up here with all this.
They were going to strike on me.
Here's a good story.
They made the freshmen, upperclassmen would make freshmen bring them some food Sunday morning or something they didn't want to go.
Well, eight demerits for taking food from the mess hall.
So they'd make the freshmen bring them some food.
Well, the freshmen get caught sometimes.
And they would give eight demerits.
That was the college rule.
The board of directors made that rule.
If you take food from the mess hall, it's eight demerits.
And demerits hurts you.
Well, after one year, I'd already made them do this and made them do that and the other.
Made them a bonfire.
They copied it and went on with it, which was fine.
I didn't have to build it the second year because they didn't quit turning, running off everybody's stuff.
They'd run off with a bunch of creosoted poles.
Well, I made them take them back.
Anything they could get there, they'd use it.
Oh, they were rough and tough in those days.
They sure were.
Somebody had to slow them down.
All right, they finally, the board of directors and the president and so forth, they just said, you believe in revolution, you don't believe in evolution.
I said, well, we've been getting nowhere in all these years I've been here, and I'm just starting.
But they said, well, listen, will you please go on back down to the athletic field?
Oh, no.
They didn't want to fire me because here I had a stack of letters and telegrams that high supporting me against them, against all these people that had the kids run off, you see, were on my side.
And they just shared the outfit with, you back that man, he's what needs, somebody needs to be done.
Well, they got me, they got me, but they just made nice for me, bent back down to something I really enjoyed doing, and we really had fun.
For the next, out of the next seven years, we won six championships in a row.
That's wonderful, that's wonderful.

So and I was having a good time and a good life, but I did get the job done because Gib Gilchrist, a Texas University graduate, was the next president of this outfit and he took my program up and we started to grow.
We started to grow.
1937, we had 34,500 students.
Now we have 35,000 students.
That's right.
Excuse me, I would like to turn the tape over just one minute.
